                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1800" notAfter="1810">
                        <p>Probably in <placeName cert="medium">London</placeName>, possibly for
                           former owner <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/299430484"
                              key="person_299430484">William Platel</persName>. Resewn on 5 raised
                           cords, laced into the <material>pasteboard</material>. Edges trimmed and
                           fully gilt, with European decorative front-bead endbands sewn in light
                           blue and bright green <material>silk</material> threads at <locus
                              from="Head" to="Head">head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail"
                              >tail</locus>. Covered full crimson Levant-grained morocco goatskin
                              <material>leather</material>, tight-backed.</p>
                        <decoNote type="binding"> Fully gilt, 'run-up' <locus from="Spine"
                              to="Spine">spine</locus> with thick-and-thin diagonals on the raised
                           bands and headcaps, with triple line fillet with a diagonal dots with
                           solid lines on either side framing the panels. Central oval radiating
                           sunburt rosettes set above a two fronds and surmounted by laurels, with
                           octafoil floral motifs on either side and fleurons in the corners. Titled
                              <q xml:lang="en">THE GARDEN OF PRAISE</q> on a maroon skiver
                              <material>leather</material> label. Boards tooled with the same triple
                           solid-dotted fillet around the perimetres, with a complex meander and
                           small foliate decorative rolls, with quatrefoil motifs on the corners,
                           all in <material>gold</material>. Board edges tooled bear the same
                           thick-and thin diagonal roll as on the spine, with interior dentelles
                           tooled with a decorative roll featuring a 'rose-thistle-shamrock' design,
                           all in <material>gold</material>. Made endpapers of dark blue coated
                           paper with European laid <material>handmade papers</material> measuring
                           ~1mm between laid lines and 24 between chain lines. These evidently
                           replaced the blue silk flyleaves described when <persName type="standard"
                              ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/79253656" key="person_79253656">Joseph
                              Butterworth Bulmer Clarke, (ca. 1797–1854)</persName> sold his
                           father's collection. <dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>231</height>
                              <width>137</width>
                              <depth>20</depth>
                           </dimensions>
                        </decoNote>
                        <condition>In good condition, with some slight abrasion to the spine,
                           headcaps, with the upper corners bumped. Areas of the gilt edge appear
                           blocked in the gutters.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
