               <history>
                  <origin>Possibly completed in either <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000235">Greater Iran</origPlace> or
                     the <origPlace cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                        >Indian subcontinent</origPlace>; undated by likely <date cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1600" notAfter="1660">early–mid 17th
                        century</date>. </origin>
                  <provenance><p> Previously owned by one <persName role="fmo seal">‘Alī Najm
                           al-Dīn</persName>, possibly the youngest of the Sayyid Brothers, Najm
                        al-Dīn ‘Alī Khān, who effectively controlled the Mughal empire after the
                        Emperor ‘Alamgīr's death in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1707"
                           >1707</date> until the rise of Muḥammad Shāh in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1717">1717</date>, at which point the volume
                        apparently entered into the Mughal royal library, until the reign of
                           <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/70169499"
                           key="person_70169499">Shāh ‘Ālam II (b. 1728, r.
                        1760–1806)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/299430484" key="person_299430484">William
                           Platel Esq. (d. 1808)</persName> of <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010809" key="place_7010809"
                           >Peterborough</placeName> from the Mughal library, after whose death the
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781"
                           key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <orgName role="auc"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134139493" key="person_134139493">Leigh &amp;
                           Sotheby</orgName> sold it in their sale commencing <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1810-12-13">13 Dec. 1810</date>, where
                           <persName role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/141371232"
                           key="person_141371232">Richard Priestley (fl. ca. 1803–1817)</persName>
                        purchased it on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1810-12-20">20 Dec.
                           1810</date> for £1, 11 shillings (p. 43 lot. 1449).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Possibly purchased from Priestley by Methodist minister <persName
                           role="fmo ins" key="person_120696480"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/120696480/">Rev. Adam Clarke
                           (1762–1832)</persName>, after whose death his son <persName role="fmo"
                           key="person_79253656" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/79253656/">Jospeh
                           Butterworth Bulmer Clarke (d. 1855)</persName> inherited the volume and
                        describes it in a catalogue that he published in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1835">1835</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>The next year on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1836-06-20">20
                           June 1836</date>, Clarke's son auctioned his father's collection through
                        the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133731879" key="person_133731879">Sotheby &amp;
                           Son</persName> where bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/34804600" key="person_34804600">William
                           Straker</persName> purchased it for £3-13s-1d.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Probably sold by Straker to Persian scholar <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                           key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803–1865)</persName>, after whose
                        death, <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> bookseller <persName type="standard"
                           role="bsl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225"
                           >Bernard Quaritch (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts in
                           <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date> to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379"
                           role="dnr">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/"
                           key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379" role="dnr"
